@page "/verify"

<PageTitle>CAI — verify</PageTitle>

<div class="hero"><div class="wrap">
    <p class="eyebrow">The proof engine</p>
    <h1>Don't trust the number. Reproduce it.</h1>
    <p class="lede">A CAI is a claim, and a claim is only as good as its reproducibility. Because an evidence bundle
        carries the measured dimensions (and a survey states its rubric version), <strong>anyone</strong> can recompute
        the headline and check it against the published number — with no access to the analyzer.</p>
</div></div>

<section><div class="wrap">
    <h2>How to verify a published survey</h2>
    <ol>
        <li><strong>Get the evidence bundle.</strong> A published survey links its evidence and states the rubric
            version it was scored under (e.g. <span class="pill">rubric-2026.08.15</span>).</li>
        <li><strong>Recompute.</strong> Fold its dimensions through the open scorer — the
            <a href="/calculator">calculator</a> does exactly this, and when the bundle carries a published
            <code>headlineScore</code> it shows the reproduction verdict inline (✓ / ✗). Or run the
            <a href="https://github.com/CanineCC/CAI">reference CLI</a>:
            <code>cai verify survey-evidence.json</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Compare.</strong> Same dimensions + same rubric ⇒ the same number. A mismatch is falsifiable proof
            the published number doesn't follow from the evidence.</li>
    </ol>
    <div class="btns">
        <a class="btn primary" href="/calculator">Open the calculator / verifier →</a>
        <a class="btn" href="/spec#evidence">The evidence format</a>
    </div>
</div></section>

<section><div class="wrap">
    <h2>Signed, so attribution is checkable too</h2>
    <p class="muted">Beyond reproducing the number, a published survey is cryptographically <strong>signed</strong> by
        its issuer — so you can confirm <em>who</em> attested it. The signature covers the content hash; the public key
        is published; anyone can verify the signature independently. Openness proves the method; the signature proves the
        author.</p>
</div></section>

<section><div class="wrap">
    <h2>It doesn't reproduce — now what?</h2>
    <p>A mismatch isn't the end of the conversation, it's the start of one. What you do next depends on <em>which</em>
        part you think is wrong — the arithmetic, the open scorer, the measurement of your code, or the rubric itself.
        Each has a documented, deliberately separate review path, and none of them asks you to trust an authority: a
        reproduction case is self-contained proof.</p>
    <div class="btns">
        <a class="btn primary" href="https://github.com/CanineCC/CAI/blob/main/docs/CHALLENGE.md">How to challenge a CAI →</a>
    </div>
</div></section>
